nosine monophosphate<br>(N6,2'-O-dibutyryl)-adenosine-3',5'-mono-phosphate<br>Dibutyryl cAMP<br>DcAMP<br>DBcAMP\n}}\n\n'''Bucladesine'''  is a cyclic nucleotide derivative which mimics the action of endogenous [[Cyclic adenosine monophosphate|cAMP]] and is a [[phosphodiesterase inhibitor]].\n\nBucladesine is a cell permeable cAMP analog. The compound is used in a wide variety of research applications because it mimics cAMP and can induce normal physiological responses when added to cells in experimental conditions. cAMP is only able to elicit minimal responses in these situations.\n\nThe [[neurite]] outgrowth instigated by bucladesine in cell cultures has been shown to be enhanced by [[nardosinone]].\n\n==Bucladesine and seizure==\nThe effect of bucladesine as a cAMP analog has been studied on the pentylenetetrazol-induced seizure in the wild-type mice. The data showed that bucladesine (300nM/mouse) reduced the seizure latency and threshold. In addition they found that combination of bucladesine and pentoxyfillin has additive effect on seizure latency and threshold.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hosseini-Zare MS, Salehi F, Seyedi SY, Azami K, Ghadiri T, Mobasseri M, Gholizadeh S, Beyer C, Sharifzadeh M |title=Effects of pentoxifylline and H-89 on epileptogenic activity of bucladesine in pentylenetetrazol-treated mice |journal=European Journal of Pharmacology |volume=670 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=464\u201370 |year=2011 |pmid=21946102 |doi=10.1016/j.ejphar.2011.09.026 }}</ref>\n\n==Bucladesine and morphine withdrawal syndrome==\nBucladesine (50-100nM/mouse) showed significant attenuation in the morphine withdrawal syndrome in the wild-type mice. In addition, its high dose (200nM/mouse) combination with [[H-89]], as a protein kinase inhibitor, had additive attenuating effect on withdrawal syndromes.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Seyedi SY, Salehi F, Payandemehr B, Hossein S, Hosseini-Zare MS, Nassireslami E, Yazdi BB, Sharifzadeh M |title=Dual effect of cAMP agonist on ameliorative function of PKA inhibitor in morphine-dependent mice |journal=Fundamental & Clinical Pharmacology |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages=445\u201354 |year=2014 |pmid=24033391 |doi=10.1111/fcp.12045 }}</ref>\n\n== Bucladesine and [[glioma]]==\nMany in vitro studies showed that treatment with bucladesine ([[dibutyryl- cyclic adenosine mono-phosphate]] = dBc-AMP) suppresses proliferation and malignancy<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maria|first=B. L.|last2=Wong|first2=D.|last3=Kalnins|first3=V. I.|date=1990|title=Dibutyryl cyclic AMP induces vimentin and GFAP expression in cultured medulloblastoma cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2155693|journal=The Canadian Journal of Neurological Sciences. Le Journal Canadien Des Sciences Neurologiques|volume=17|issue=1|pages=15\u201320|doi=10.1017/s0317167100029954|issn=0317-1671|pmid=2155693|via=}}</ref> enhances cytoplasmic process formation and increases cytoplasmic glial fibrillary acidic protein ([[Glial fibrillary acidic protein|GFAP]]) <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pilkington|first=G. J.|last2=Darling|first2=J. L.|last3=Lantos|first3=P. L.|last4=Thomas|first4=D. G.|date=1983|title=Cell lines (VMDk) derived from a spontaneous murine astrocytoma. Morphological and immunocytochemical characterization|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6321667|journal=Journal of the Neurological Sciences|volume=62|issue=1-3|pages=115\u2013139|doi=10.1016/0022-510x(83)90193-4|issn=0022-510X|pmid=6321667|via=}}</ref>, suppressing malignant glioma invasion by decreasing the expression of [[CD44]] isoforms <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sakai|first=H.|last2=Nakashima|first2=S.|last3=Yoshimura|first3=S.|last4=Nakatani|first4=K.|last5=Shinoda|first5=J.|last6=Sakai|first6=N.|last7=Yamada|first7=H.|last8=Nozawa|first8=Y.|date=1996-06-07|title=Suppressed expression of CD44 variant isoforms during human glioma A172 cell differentiation induced by cyclic AMP|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8805127|journal=Neuroscience Letters|volume=210|issue=3|pages=189\u2013192|doi=10.1016/0304-3940(96)12683-5|issn=0304-3940|pmid=8805127}}</ref>''.'' Thus it has been concluded that bucladesine can induce biochemical and morphological changes in cultured glioma cells <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boghaert|first=E. R.|last2=Simpson|first2=J.|last3=Jacob|first3=R. J.|last4=Lacey|first4=T.|last5=Walsh|first5=J. W.|last6=Zimmer|first6=S. G.|date=1991-02-20|title=The effect of dibutyryl camp (dBcAMP) on morphological differentiation, growth and invasion in vitro of a hamster brain-tumor cell line: a comparative study of dBcAMP effects in 2- and 3-dimensional cultures|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1847358|journal=International Journal of Cancer|volume=47|issue=4|pages=610\u2013618|doi=10.1002/ijc.2910470422|issn=0020-7136|pmid=1847358}}</ref>''.''. [[Flow cytometry|Flow cytometric]] analysis on the cell cycle of the 9L rat glioma showed that cAMP can arrest the cells in the G1 phase and induces 9L cells into resting position (G0 cells). On the other hand SNAP ([[S-Nitroso-N-acetylpenicillamine|S-nitroso-N-acetylpenicillamine]])-induced p53-sensitive cell death and [[DNA fragmentation]] were enhanced and [[Bcl-2]] was decreased by pretreatment with bucladesine (dBc-AMP). Bucladesine induces a decreased Bcl-2 level and enhances [[MPP]]+-induced cell death thus dBc-AMP sensitized the cells to induction of apoptosis. Both mechanisms are indicating the role of bucladesine in the [[p53]]-[[apoptosis]] phenomena. Inhibitory impact of [[bucladesine]] on the migration pattern of astrocytes grafted into adult rat brain is shown. Studies demonstrate significant growth delay (up to 69%) by dBc-AMP in an experimental trial on multicellular spheroids derived directly from human [[Brain tumor|malignant brain tumors]] in vitro<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oktar|first=N.|last2=Darling|first2=J. L.|last3=Thomas|first3=D. G.|date=1987|title=An experimental trial of cyclic nucleotides on multicellular spheroids derived from human brain tumours|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3037037|journal=Journal of Neuro-Oncology|volume=5|issue=1|pages=83\u201389|doi=10.1007/bf00162770|issn=0167-594X|pmid=3037037}}</ref>. In vivo administration of bucladesine loaded [[Biodegradable polymer|biodegradable]] polymeric sustained release (bcl-SR) discs did not showed any neurotoxicity effect on the rat brain tissue. In a randomized prospective phase II trial of local interstitial chemotherapy with bcl-SR did show a delay of recurrence in the treatment of ''de novo'' [[glioblastoma]] patients<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dalbasti|first=Tayfun|last2=Oktar|first2=Nezih|last3=Cagli|first3=Sedat|last4=Ozdamar|first4=Nurcan|date=2002|title=Local interstitial chemotherapy with sustained release bucladesine in de novo glioblastoma multiforme: a preliminary study|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11995818|journal=Journal of Neuro-Oncology|volume=56|issue=2|pages=167\u2013174|doi=10.1023/a:1014583820223|issn=0167-594X|pmid=11995818|via=}}</ref>.\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MeshName|Bucladesine}}\n\n{{Phosphodiesterase inhibitors}}\n{{Cardiac stimulants excluding cardiac glycosides}}\n\n[[Category:Nucleotides]]\n[[Category:Carboxamides]]\n[[Category:PDE3 inhibitors]]\n\n\n{{cardiovascular-drug-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 443480569\n| IUPAC_name = boring(3a''R'',4''R'',6''R'',6a''R'')-4-(6-butanamido-9''H''-purin-9-yl)-6-[(butanoyloxy)methyl]-2-oxo-tetrahydro-2''H''-1,3,5,2\u03bb<sup>5</sup>-furo[3,4-d][1,3,2]dioxaphosphol-2-olate\n| image = Bucladesine.svg\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| Drugs.com = {{drugs.com|international|bucladesine}}\n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B            / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category =  \n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4  / S8 -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL         / P       / POM / CD -->\n| legal_US = <!-- OTC                   / Rx-onl