la M. |last2= Bertacchi |first2= Cristina |editor-last= Villoresi |editor-first= Valerio |title= Lombard villas and stately homes |publisher= AdArte |location= Turin |year= 2014|date= |orig-year= |pages= 56\u201371 |chapter= Three castles in one: Castello Visconti di San Vito, Somma Lombardo (Varese) |chapterurl= |isbn= 9788889082546 |lastauthoramp=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Hale |first= John Rigby |authorlink=John Rigby Hale |title= A concise encyclopaedia of the Italian Renaissance |volume= |series= |edition=|publisher= Thames & Hudson |year=1981 |oclc=636355191 |isbn= |language= |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Gamberini |first=Andrea |editor-last= Gamberini |editor-first= Andrea |title= A companion to late medieval and early modern Milan. The distinctive features of an Italian state |publisher= Brill |location= Leiden, Boston |year= 2014|orig-year= |pages=19\u201345 |chapter=Milan and Lombardy in the era of the Visconti and the Sforza |chapterurl= |isbn=9789004284128 |lastauthoramp= |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Jones |first= Philip James |title=The Italian city-state from commune to signoria |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford & New York  |year=1997 |isbn=9786610806577 |oclc=252653924 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Keller |first=Hagen |title=Adelsherrschaft und st\u00e4dtische Gesellschaft in Oberitalien, 9. bis 12. Jahrhundert |trans-title=Nobility and urban society in northern Italy, 9th to 12th centuries |volume=52 |publisher=M. Niemeyer Verlag |location=T\u00fcbingen |year=1979 |isbn=9783484800885 |oclc=612442612 |language=de |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Litta Biumi |first=Pompeo |title=Famiglie celebri italiane |trans-title= |chapter=Visconti di Milano |location=Milano |publisher=Luciano Basadonna Editore |year=1823 |oclc=|language=it |ref=harv |hdl=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Menant |first=Fran\u00e7ois |title=L'Italie des communes (1100\u20131350) |trans-title=Italy of the communes |volume=|series= |edition=|publisher=\u00c9dition Belin |year=2005 |isbn=9782701140445 |language=fr|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia |last=Simeoni |first=Luigi |title = Visconti da Oleggio |encyclopedia = [[Treccani|Enciclopedia Italiana di Scienze, Lettere ed Arti]] |date = |year=1937 |publisher=Istituto dell'Enciclopedia Italiana |location=|id =|url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/visconti-da-oleggio_%28Enciclopedia-Italiana%29/ |access-date={{date|2020-04-12}}|language=it |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Visconti |first=Alessandro |title=Storia di Milano. A cura della Famiglia Meneghina e sotto gli auspici del Comune di Milano |trans-title=History of Milan. Edited by Famiglia Meneghina and under the auspices of the Commune of Milan |location=Milano |publisher=Ceschina |year=1967 |oclc=2872335 |language=it |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Wilkins |first=Ernest Hatch |title=Petrarch's eight years in Milan |location=Cambridge, MA, US |publisher=Mediaeval Academy of America |year=1958 |oclc=926390871 |ref=harv |hdl=2027/heb.31117 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Williams |first=George L. |title=Papal genealogy: The families and descendants of the popes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mq7ctwMNdoC&lpg=PA34&dq=%22Luchino%20Visconti%22%201349&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q=(%22Luchino%20Visconti%22%20OR%20%22Lucchino%20Visconti%22)%201349&f=false |accessdate=September 16, 2010 |year=1998 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]] |location=Jefferson, NC |isbn=9780786403158 |oclc=301275208 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Visconti of Milan}}\n{{Royal houses of Europe}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Visconti, House Of}}\n[[Category:House of Visconti| ]]\n[[Category:Rulers of Milan]]\n", "name_user": "Bg69", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed references to litta biumi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visconti_of_Milan"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664)", "text_new": "{{For|the battle in the Rak\u00f3czi's War for Independence|Battle of Saint Gotthard (1705)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2010}}\n{{Expand Hungarian|/Szentgotth\u00e1rdi csata (1664)|topic=hist|date=August 2009}}\n{{Expand Turkish|St. Gotthard Muharebesi (1664)|date=December 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Saint Gotthard\n|partof=the [[Austro-Turkish War (1663\u20131664)]]\n|image=Mogersdorf1.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Battle of Saint Gotthard\n|date=August 1, 1664\n|place=[[Szentgotth\u00e1rd]], [[Vas|Vas County]], along the present-day Austro-Hungarian border\n|result=Decisive League victory\n|combatant1='''[[League of the Rhine]]:'''<br />\n{{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}<br />\n{{flag|Holy Roman Empire}}<br />\n* {{flagcountry|Electorate of Saxony}}\n* {{flagicon image|Pabellon_de_Brandeburgo_(c._1684).svg}} [[Brandenburg-Prussia]]\n* {{flagicon|Bavaria}} [[Electorate of Bavaria|Bavaria]]\n* {{flagicon image|Banner_of_Baden_(3%5E2).svg|22px}} [[Margraviate of Baden]]\n* [[File:Coat of arms of the Swabian League.svg|20px]] [[Swabia]]\n{{flag|Duchy of Savoy|name=Piedmont-Savoy}}<br />\n''[[League of the Rhine|et al.]]''\n|combatant2=[[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] '''[[Ottoman Empire]]'''<br />\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the crimeans.svg}} [[Crimean Khanate]]\n* {{flag|Moldavia|1646}}\n* {{flag|Wallachia|1639}}\n|commander1={{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]] <br /> {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Johann von Sporck]]{{sfn|Stieve|1893|pp=266\u2013267}} <br />{{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Leopold Wilhelm, Margrave of Baden-Baden|Margrave von Baden]]<br />{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Jean de Coligny-Saligny|Comte de Coligny]]<br />{{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Prince Georg Friedrich of Waldeck|Prince Waldeck]]\n|commander2=[[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fczade Faz\u0131l Ahmed Pasha]] \n|strength1=~26-28,000,<ref name=\"G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s 1664\">G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s: The Battle of Szentgotth\u00e1rd (1664), ''Vasi Szemle (Vas Review)'', 1964.</ref> or 40,000<ref>Black & Murphey, ''Ottoman Warfare, 1500-1700'', pp.48-49 \"At the battle of Saint Gotthard in August 1664 Raimondo Montecuccolli, supreme commander of a Habsburg force significantly strengthened by units both from France and the Rhine confederates, still only managed to field an army of some 40,000 men.\"</ref>\n|strength2=~ 50,000-60,000 (30,000 remained unengaged<ref>Wilson, ''German Armies: War and German Politics, 1648-1806'', p. 43 \"Energetic recruiting had increased Habsburg forces to 51,000 by February 1664, supported by 9,000 Hungarians, but disease and the need to garrison border fortresses reduced the combined force to 24,450 by the time Montecucolli engaged the 50,000-60,000 strong Ottoman army at the Monastery of St Gotthard on the river Raab on 1 August 1664. [...] Though 30,000 of his troops remained unengaged, the grand visier sensed the battle going against him and decided to retreat, leaving the Christians in possession of the field. Two thousand, mainly Germans, had been lost, along with similar number of fugitives. Turkish losses are not known, but were probably less.\"</ref>), or ~60,000 janissaries, and sipahi<br/>60-90,000 irregular<ref name=\"G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s 1664\" />\n|casualties1=2-6,000\n|casualties2=16-22,000<ref name=\"G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s 1664\" />\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Austro-Turkish War (1663-1664)}}\n{{Campaignbox Ottoman-Habsburg Wars}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Saint Gotthard''' ({{lang-hu|Szentgotth\u00e1rdi csata}}; {{lang-tr|Saint Gotthard Muharebesi}}; {{lang-de|Schlacht bei Mogersdorf}} and {{lang|de|Schlacht bei St. Gotthard}}; {{lang-fr|Bataille de Saint-Gothard}}) was fought on August 1, 1664 as part of the [[Austro-Turkish War (1663\u20131664)]], between the [[Imperial Army (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Army]] led by Generalleutnant [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]], [[Jean de Coligny-Saligny]], [[Wolfgang Julius, Count of Hohenlohe-Neuenstein]], together with the [[Army of the Holy Roman Empire]] led by [[Generalfeldmarschall|Reichsgeneralfeldmarschall]] [[Leopold Wilhelm of Baden-Baden|Prince Leopold of Baden]] and Reichsgeneralfeldmarschalleutnant [[Prince Georg Friedrich of Waldeck|Georg Friedrich of Waldeck]] and the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|army]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] under the command of [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fczade Faz\u0131l Ahmed Pasha|K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc Faz\u0131l Ahmed Pa\u015fa]].\n\nThe battle took place near [[Szentgotth\u00e1rd]] and [[Mogersdorf]] in Western [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]], near the present-day Austro-Hungarian border and is known as the Battle of Mogersdorf in Austria. The Turks were militarily defeated but were able to negotiate the [[Peace of Vasv\u00e1r]], which was highly favorable to them.<ref>[http://mek.oszk.hu/01900/01911/html/index8.html Cross and Crescent]</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\nOttoman dominance in Hungary began with the [[Battle of Moh\u00e1cs]] in 1526, which resulted in the conquest of most of Hungary by [[Suleiman the Magnificent]]. Meanwhile, the parts of Hungary that remained under Austrian control became known as [[Royal Hungary]]. Although the Ottomans had been in relative decline since the death of Suleiman I, Ottoman power saw a resurgence under the extremely capable [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc family]] who sought to destroy the Austrian Habsburgs once and for all. They found their ''[[casus belli]]'' when the Habsburgs supported a Transylvanian rebellion against Ottoman rule.\n\n[[Transylvania]] had escaped Ottoman conquest during the invasion of Hungary and retained its independence by playing off of their powerful neighbors: [[Poland]], Austria and the Ottomans. They recognized Ottoman suzerainty and paid a tribute to the [[Ottoman Porte|Porte]] but were given political and religious autonomy in return. In 1658, seeking new land for his principality, Prince [[George II R\u00e1k\u00f3czi|George R\u00e1k\u00f3czy II]] invaded Poland with his [[Sweden|Swedish]] allies in the [[Northern Wars|Second Northern War]]. After initial success, he was defeated by the Poles and fled back to Transylvania. On hearing about R\u00e1k\u00f3czy's unauthorized war, the Ottomans declared war on their vassal. It was not long before [[Grand Vizier]] [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc Mehmed Pasha]] (Vizier 1656-1661) defeated R\u00e1k\u00f3czy and conquered Transylvania. The new Transylvanian prince, [[John Kem\u00e9ny (Prince)|J\u00e1nos Kem\u00e9ny]], fled to Vienna, seeking Austrian support.\n\nEmperor [[Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor|Leopold I]], not wishing to see Transylvania fall under direct Ottoman control, sent Montecuccoli into Hungary with his small army. Montecuccoli gave no direct support as he was severely outnumbered by the Ottomans. The Ottomans, meanwhile, completed the conquest of Transylvania {{Citation needed|date=February 2009}} and built up their forces in Ottoman Hungary. Leopold I, not wishing to face the Turks alone, summoned the [[Diet (assembly)|Imperial Diet]] in January 1663.\n\nThe Turks failed to conquer the fortress of [[Nov\u00e9 Z\u00e1mky]] six times, but managed to do so in 1663. It was made the center of an Ottoman province, the [[Uyvar eyalet]] in present-day southern [[Slovakia]]. Turks and Tatars crossed the Danube in strength in 1663, ravaging Slovakia, [[Moravia]], and [[Silesia]]. They took 12,000 slaves in Moravia. Several Turkish divisions reached as far as [[Olomouc]].<ref>[http://www.olomouc-tourism.cz/index.php?lang=2&kategorie=158&clanek=42 Olomouc History]</ref>\n\n[[Image:VasCounty.gif|thumb|left|Vas County - Hungary]]\n\n==Diplomatic efforts==\nAlthough Leopold personally objected to [[Protestantism]], he had to rely on his Protestant German princes to provide military aid. Even worse was the military aid from [[France]], which was (and continued to be until the [[Diplomatic Revolution]] of 1756) Austria's nemesis. Despite numerous objections from some Protestant princes, help was not withheld. The [[League of the Rhine]] - a French dominated group of German princes - agreed to send a corps of 6,000 men independently commanded by Count Coligny of France and Prince [[Johann Philipp von Sch\u00f6nborn|Johann Philipp of Mainz]]. By September 1663, [[Brandenburg]] and [[Saxony]] had also agreed to contingents of their own. In January 1664, the Imperial Diet agreed to raise 21,000 men, although this army did not yet exist other than on paper. The Turks had declared war in April 1663, but were slow in executing their invasion plans.\n\n==Battle==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2016}}\nK\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc's army, which might have numbered 120-150,000, probably included some 60,000 [[Janissary|Janissaries]] and [[sipahi]]s, 60-90,000 [[azap]]s, [[ak\u0131nc\u0131]]s, [[silidar]]s, [[Tatars]] and [[vassal]]s and allegedly 360 guns.\n\n[[Image:Raimondo-montecuccoli.jpg|thumb|left|Raimondo Montecuccoli]]\n\nMontecuccoli's army consisted of Habsburg forces (including [[Czechs|Czech]] infantry and a few hundred Hungarians, approx. 2,000 Croatians) and forces from the German principalities, French brigades,  a [[Piedmont]]ese regiment .\n\n'''The Habsburg forces:''' 5,000 infantry (10 Battalions), 5,900 cavalry (27 escadrons), 10 guns<br />\n'''The Imperial forces:''' 6,200 infantry (6 Battalions), 1,200 cavalry (9 escadrons), 14 guns<br />\n'''The Rhine forces:''' 600 infantry (2 Battalions), 300 cavalry (4 escadrons)<br />\n'''The French forces:''' 3,500 infantry (4 Battalions), 1,750 cavalry (10 escadrons)<br />\n'''Other forces:''' 2,000 Croat cavalry (out of this a regiment), Hungarian foot soldiers in [[Szentgotth\u00e1rd]], and Esterh\u00e1zy, Batthy\u00e1ny and N\u00e1dasdy regiment's, Czech [[musketeer]]s and the Italian (Piedmontish) infantry regiment (commander [[Francesco Pio de Savoya|Marchese Pio de Savoya]]).\n\nThe Turks renewed their invasion in the spring of 1664. They [[Siege of Novi Zrin (1664)|besieged, conquered and destroyed]] [[Novi Zrin|Novi Zrin Fortress]] on the [[Mur River|Mura]] river in [[northern Croatia]] at the very beginning of July. Montecuccoli was still waiting for help to arrive, and this delay was key to the defense of Austria. In July 1664 the Imperial forces were assembled and set out for the River [[R\u00e1ba]], which separated the Ottoman forces from the Austrian duchy itself. If the Turks were allowed to cross, they would threaten both Vienna and [[Graz]]. Montecuccoli intercepted the Turks before they crossed the river but the division of command made effective deployment of troops impossible.\n\nOn 1 August 1664, Ottoman forces crossed the river near the monastery of [[Gotthard of Hildesheim|Saint Gotthar]]d and beat the Austrians back. Although initially plagued by disunity, Montecuccoli was finally able to convince Coligny and Leopold Wilhelm of Baden-Baden (commander of the Imperial detachment) to mass their forces and attack the Ottoman troops, who were reorganizing in a nearby forest. The attack surprised the Turks, who fled in confusion back to the river, a large number drowning. The confusion caused by the fleeing troops prevented Ahmed K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc (Vizier 1661-1676) from sending the rest of his army across the river and he instead retired from the field.\n\n[[File:A szentgotth\u00e1rdi csata (n\u00e9met k\u00e9p).jpg|thumb|250px|The Battle in an engraving of the era.]]\n\nOttoman casualties were heavy, significantly falling mostly on the elite corps of the army. K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc was left with an army of ill-trained irregulars and auxiliaries while Montecuccoli's casualties were light and mostly in the Imperial contingent.\n\n[[Image:Schl\u00f6sslbergi k\u0151kereszt.jpg|thumb|right|Stonecross of Sch\u00f6sslberg, over Mogersdorf; monument of the Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664).]]\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2016}}\nAlthough many in Europe, especially the [[Croats]] and [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] nobility, expected the Austrian Habsburgs to finally liberate Hungary once and for all, Leopold abandoned the campaign. Many have criticized him for this decision (both in the past and the present). Although Montecuccoli's army was largely intact, there was no interest among the allies to liberate Hungary. Any invasion of Hungary would undoubtedly have to be done without the help of the French and German troops. Leopold noticed that the French officers had begun to fraternize with the Magyar nobles and encouraged them to rebel against Austrian rule.\n\nIn addition, Leopold had always been a member of the \"Spanish faction\" in Vienna. With the last [[Habsburg Spain|Spanish Habsburg]], [[Charles II of Spain|Carlos II]], about to die at any given moment, Leopold wanted to ensure that his hands were free for the inevitable struggle against [[Louis XIV of France]]. Although the liberation of Hungary was a strategic interest of the Habsburgs, it would have to wait until later. Throughout his reign, Leopold had always been more interested in the struggle against France rather than the Ottomans. Therefore, he signed the rather unfavourable [[Peace of Vasv\u00e1r]], which did not take into account the Battle of Saint Gotthard. The Battle of Saint Gotthard is still significant, however, for it stopped any Ottoman invasion of Austria, which certainly would have prolonged the war and led to a disastrous resolution. The Austrians would also use the twenty-year truce to build up their forces and begin the liberation of Hungary in 1683.\n\n==In literature==\nThe battle of Mogersdorf/Szentgotth\u00e1rd provided [[Rainer Maria Rilke]] with the inspiration for his poetic short story, \"[[:de:Die Weise von Liebe und Tod des Cornets Christoph Rilke|Lay of the Love and Death of Cornet Christopher Rilke]]\", which was very popular among German and Austrian soldiers during the first half of the 20th century.\n\n== Evliya \u00c7elebi and bullet extraction from the intracranial cavity via \u201c[[Trepanning|trephination]]\u201d ==\nIn the 7th volume of his ''Seyahatname'', the Turkish traveller [[Evliya \u00c7elebi|Evliy\u00e2 \u00c7elebi]] recounts the journey of Austria in the year 1665 in a long chapter. According to his anectodal travelogue, Evliy\u00e2 \u00c7elebi visited the Hospital of [[St. Stephen's Cathedral, Vienna|Saint Stephan's Cathedral]] on the banks of the [[Danube]] in the city of [[Vienna]] as a member of an Ottoman embassy in 1665, after the [[Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664)|Battle of Saint Gotthard]] between an Ottoman army under the command of [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fczade Faz\u0131l Ahmed Pasha|K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc Faz\u0131l Ahmed]] and an Habsburg army led by [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]], Jean de Coligny-Saligny, Wolfgang Julius von Hohenlohe, Prince Leopold of Baden, and Georg Friedrich of Waldeck on the [[R\u00e1ba|river Raab]] on August 1, 1664 <ref>{{Cite journal|last=K\u00f6kmen|first=E.|date=1972|title=A fantastic craniotomy: excerpt from the 17th century Turkish travelogue of Evliy\u00e2 Celebi. Case report|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/4556579|journal=Journal of Neurosurgery|volume=37|issue=1|pages=103\u2013104|doi=10.3171/jns.1972.37.1.0103|issn=0022-3085|pmid=4556579|via=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mossensohn|first=Miri Shefer|date=2008|title=An Ottoman observer of central European surgery in the middle of the seventeenth century|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19579333|journal=Vesalius: Acta Internationales Historiae Medicinae|volume=14|issue=1|pages=4\u20137|issn=1373-4857|pmid=19579333|via=}}</ref>,. The following extraordinary account taken from this volume gives an original description of the neurosurgical technique for bullet extraction from the intracranial cavity via \u201ctrephination\u201d. In the aforementioned account, Evliy\u00e2 \u00c7elebi reported one of the earliest operations for the bullet extraction in that the surgeon of brain trephined over the bone, removed a bullet under the cranium, and placed a wick for drainage. In fact, he described his observation regarding the relationship between the Ottoman medical system and European medicine. Now, he is justified as a man of [[Istanbul]], gentleman, reporter, entertainer, raconteur, and [[dervish]] in the 17th century [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman period]]. It is interesting to note that some of the surgical and aseptic techniques mentioned are still valid in the medical and scientific world<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Turgut|first=Mehmet|date=2010-08-01|title=An account describing an operation for the bullet extraction from the middle of 17th century Ottoman traveller Evliy\u00e2 \u00c7elebi (1611\u20131682 ad)|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00381-010-1132-z|journal=Child's Nervous System|language=en|volume=26|issue=8|pages=989\u2013990|doi=10.1007/s00381-010-1132-z|issn=1433-0350}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|War}}\n* [[Battle of Saint Gotthard (1705)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons and category|Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664)|Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664)}}\n* {{Cite ADB|35|264|267|Sporck, Johann Graf von|Felix Stieve|ADB:Sporck, Johann Graf von|ref=CITEREF1893Stieve}}\n* Jeremy Black & Rhoads Murphey, ''Ottoman Warfare, 1500-1700'', Routledge, 1999.\n* Peter H. Wilson, ''German Armies: War and German Politics, 1648-1806'', Routledge, 1998.\n*[[John P. Spielman]], ''Leopold I of Austria'' (1977) {{ISBN|0-8135-0836-3}}\n*[[Charles W. Ingrao]], ''The Habsburg Monarchy 1618-1815'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-521-78505-7}}\n\n{{Coord|46|56|30|N|16|13|00|E|dim:250_scale:2500_region:AT-1_type:event_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n{{Ottoman battles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Gotthard (1664), Battle Of}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1664]]\n[[Category:1664 in the Habsburg Monarchy]]\n[[Category:Vas County]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Hungary]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Austria|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Ottoman\u2013Hungarian Wars|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Ottoman Empire|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Moldavia|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Slovenes|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Habsburg Croatia|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Austro-Turkish War (1663\u201364)|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:1664 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1664 in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Wallachia]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the battle in the Rak\u00f3czi's War for Independence|Battle of Saint Gotthard (1705)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2010}}\n{{Expand Hungarian|/Szentgotth\u00e1rdi csata (1664)|topic=hist|date=August 2009}}\n{{Expand Turkish|St. Gotthard Muharebesi (1664)|date=December 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Saint Gotthard\n|partof=the [[Austro-Turkish War (1663\u20131664)]]\n|image=Mogersdorf1.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Battle of Saint Gotthard\n|date=August 1, 1664\n|place=[[Szentgotth\u00e1rd]], [[Vas|Vas County]], along the present-day Austro-Hungarian border\n|result=Decisive League victory\n|combatant1='''[[League of the Rhine]]:'''<br />\n{{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}<br />\n{{flag|Holy Roman Empire}}<br />\n* {{flagcountry|Electorate of Saxony}}\n* {{flagicon image|Pabellon_de_Brandeburgo_(c._1684).svg}} [[Brandenburg-Prussia]]\n* {{flagicon|Bavaria}} [[Electorate of Bavaria|Bavaria]]\n* {{flagicon image|Banner_of_Baden_(3%5E2).svg|22px}} [[Margraviate of Baden]]\n* [[File:Coat of arms of the Swabian League.svg|20px]] [[Swabia]]\n{{flag|Duchy of Savoy|name=Piedmont-Savoy}}<br />\n''[[League of the Rhine|et al.]]''\n|combatant2=[[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] '''[[Ottoman Empire]]'''<br />\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the crimeans.svg}} [[Crimean Khanate]]\n* {{flag|Moldavia|1646}}\n* {{flag|Wallachia|1639}}\n|commander1={{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]] <br /> {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Johann von Sporck]]{{sfn|Stieve|1893|pp=266\u2013267}} <br />{{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Leopold Wilhelm, Margrave of Baden-Baden|Margrave von Baden]]<br />{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Jean de Coligny-Saligny|Comte de Coligny]]<br />{{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Prince Georg Friedrich of Waldeck|Prince Waldeck]]\n|commander2=[[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fczade Faz\u0131l Ahmed Pasha]] \n|strength1=~26-28,000,<ref name=\"G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s 1664\">G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s: The Battle of Szentgotth\u00e1rd (1664), ''Vasi Szemle (Vas Review)'', 1964.</ref> or 40,000<ref>Black & Murphey, ''Ottoman Warfare, 1500-1700'', pp.48-49 \"At the battle of Saint Gotthard in August 1664 Raimondo Montecuccolli, supreme commander of a Habsburg force significantly strengthened by units both from France and the Rhine confederates, still only managed to field an army of some 40,000 men.\"</ref>\n|strength2=~ 50,000-60,000 (30,000 remained unengaged<ref>Wilson, ''German Armies: War and German Politics, 1648-1806'', p. 43 \"Energetic recruiting had increased Habsburg forces to 51,000 by February 1664, supported by 9,000 Hungarians, but disease and the need to garrison border fortresses reduced the combined force to 24,450 by the time Montecucolli engaged the 50,000-60,000 strong Ottoman army at the Monastery of St Gotthard on the river Raab on 1 August 1664. [...] Though 30,000 of his troops remained unengaged, the grand visier sensed the battle going against him and decided to retreat, leaving the Christians in possession of the field. Two thousand, mainly Germans, had been lost, along with similar number of fugitives. Turkish losses are not known, but were probably less.\"</ref>), or ~60,000 janissaries, and sipahi<br/>60-90,000 irregular<ref name=\"G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s 1664\" />\n|casualties1=2-6,000\n|casualties2=16-22,000<ref name=\"G\u00e9za Perj\u00e9s 1664\" />\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Austro-Turkish War (1663-1664)}}\n{{Campaignbox Ottoman-Habsburg Wars}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Saint Gotthard''' ({{lang-hu|Szentgotth\u00e1rdi csata}}; {{lang-tr|Saint Gotthard Muharebesi}}; {{lang-de|Schlacht bei Mogersdorf}} and {{lang|de|Schlacht bei St. Gotthard}}; {{lang-fr|Bataille de Saint-Gothard}}) was fought on August 1, 1664 as part of the [[Austro-Turkish War (1663\u20131664)]], between the [[Imperial Army (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Army]] led by Generalleutnant [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]], [[Jean de Coligny-Saligny]], [[Wolfgang Julius, Count of Hohenlohe-Neuenstein]], together with the [[Army of the Holy Roman Empire]] led by [[Generalfeldmarschall|Reichsgeneralfeldmarschall]] [[Leopold Wilhelm of Baden-Baden|Prince Leopold of Baden]] and Reichsgeneralfeldmarschalleutnant [[Prince Georg Friedrich of Waldeck|Georg Friedrich of Waldeck]] and the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|army]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] under the command of [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fczade Faz\u0131l Ahmed Pasha|K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc Faz\u0131l Ahmed Pa\u015fa]].\n\nThe battle took place near [[Szentgotth\u00e1rd]] and [[Mogersdorf]] in Western [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]], near the present-day Austro-Hungarian border and is known as the Battle of Mogersdorf in Austria. The Turks were militarily defeated but were able to negotiate the [[Peace of Vasv\u00e1r]], which was highly favorable to them.<ref>[http://mek.oszk.hu/01900/01911/html/index8.html Cross and Crescent]</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\nOttoman dominance in Hungary began with the [[Battle of Moh\u00e1cs]] in 1526, which resulted in the conquest of most of Hungary by [[Suleiman the Magnificent]]. Meanwhile, the parts of Hungary that remained under Austrian control became known as [[Royal Hungary]]. Although the Ottomans had been in relative decline since the death of Suleiman I, Ottoman power saw a resurgence under the extremely capable [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc family]] who sought to destroy the Austrian Habsburgs once and for all. They found their ''[[casus belli]]'' when the Habsburgs supported a Transylvanian rebellion against Ottoman rule.\n\n[[Transylvania]] had escaped Ottoman conquest during the invasion of Hungary and retained its independence by playing off of their powerful neighbors: [[Poland]], Austria and the Ottomans. They recognized Ottoman suzerainty and paid a tribute to the [[Ottoman Porte|Porte]] but were given political and religious autonomy in return. In 1658, seeking new land for his principality, Prince [[George II R\u00e1k\u00f3czi|George R\u00e1k\u00f3czy II]] invaded Poland with his [[Sweden|Swedish]] allies in the [[Northern Wars|Second Northern War]]. After initial success, he was defeated by the Poles and fled back to Transylvania. On hearing about R\u00e1k\u00f3czy's unauthorized war, the Ottomans declared war on their vassal. It was not long before [[Grand Vizier]] [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc Mehmed Pasha]] (Vizier 1656-1661) defeated R\u00e1k\u00f3czy and conquered Transylvania. The new Transylvanian prince, [[John Kem\u00e9ny (Prince)|J\u00e1nos Kem\u00e9ny]], fled to Vienna, seeking Austrian support.\n\nEmperor [[Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor|Leopold I]], not wishing to see Transylvania fall under direct Ottoman control, sent Montecuccoli into Hungary with his small army. Montecuccoli gave no direct support as he was severely outnumbered by the Ottomans. The Ottomans, meanwhile, completed the conquest of Transylvania {{Citation needed|date=February 2009}} and built up their forces in Ottoman Hungary. Leopold I, not wishing to face the Turks alone, summoned the [[Diet (assembly)|Imperial Diet]] in January 1663.\n\nThe Turks failed to conquer the fortress of [[Nov\u00e9 Z\u00e1mky]] six times, but managed to do so in 1663. It was made the center of an Ottoman province, the [[Uyvar eyalet]] in present-day southern [[Slovakia]]. Turks and Tatars crossed the Danube in strength in 1663, ravaging Slovakia, [[Moravia]], and [[Silesia]]. They took 12,000 slaves in Moravia. Several Turkish divisions reached as far as [[Olomouc]].<ref>[http://www.olomouc-tourism.cz/index.php?lang=2&kategorie=158&clanek=42 Olomouc History]</ref>\n\n[[Image:VasCounty.gif|thumb|left|Vas County - Hungary]]\n\n==Diplomatic efforts==\nAlthough Leopold personally objected to [[Protestantism]], he had to rely on his Protestant German princes to provide military aid. Even worse was the military aid from [[France]], which was (and continued to be until the [[Diplomatic Revolution]] of 1756) Austria's nemesis. Despite numerous objections from some Protestant princes, help was not withheld. The [[League of the Rhine]] - a French dominated group of German princes - agreed to send a corps of 6,000 men independently commanded by Count Coligny of France and Prince [[Johann Philipp von Sch\u00f6nborn|Johann Philipp of Mainz]]. By September 1663, [[Brandenburg]] and [[Saxony]] had also agreed to contingents of their own. In January 1664, the Imperial Diet agreed to raise 21,000 men, although this army did not yet exist other than on paper. The Turks had declared war in April 1663, but were slow in executing their invasion plans.\n\n==Battle==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2016}}\nK\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc's army, which might have numbered 120-150,000, probably included some 60,000 [[Janissary|Janissaries]] and [[sipahi]]s, 60-90,000 [[azap]]s, [[ak\u0131nc\u0131]]s, [[silidar]]s, [[Tatars]] and [[vassal]]s and allegedly 360 guns.\n\n[[Image:Raimondo-montecuccoli.jpg|thumb|left|Raimondo Montecuccoli]]\n\nMontecuccoli's army consisted of Habsburg forces (including [[Czechs|Czech]] infantry and a few hundred Hungarians, approx. 2,000 Croatians) and forces from the German principalities, French brigades,  a [[Piedmont]]ese regiment .\n\n'''The Habsburg forces:''' 5,000 infantry (10 Battalions), 5,900 cavalry (27 escadrons), 10 guns<br />\n'''The Imperial forces:''' 6,200 infantry (6 Battalions), 1,200 cavalry (9 escadrons), 14 guns<br />\n'''The Rhine forces:''' 600 infantry (2 Battalions), 300 cavalry (4 escadrons)<br />\n'''The French forces:''' 3,500 infantry (4 Battalions), 1,750 cavalry (10 escadrons)<br />\n'''Other forces:''' 2,000 Croat cavalry (out of this a regiment), Hungarian foot soldiers in [[Szentgotth\u00e1rd]], and Esterh\u00e1zy, Batthy\u00e1ny and N\u00e1dasdy regiment's, Czech [[musketeer]]s and the Italian (Piedmontish) infantry regiment (commander [[Francesco Pio de Savoya|Marchese Pio de Savoya]]).\n\nThe Turks renewed their invasion in the spring of 1664. They [[Siege of Novi Zrin (1664)|besieged, conquered and destroyed]] [[Novi Zrin|Novi Zrin Fortress]] on the [[Mur River|Mura]] river in [[northern Croatia]] at the very beginning of July. Montecuccoli was still waiting for help to arrive, and this delay was key to the defense of Austria. In July 1664 the Imperial forces were assembled and set out for the River [[R\u00e1ba]], which separated the Ottoman forces from the Austrian duchy itself. If the Turks were allowed to cross, they would threaten both Vienna and [[Graz]]. Montecuccoli intercepted the Turks before they crossed the river but the division of command made effective deployment of troops impossible.\n\nOn 1 August 1664, Ottoman forces crossed the river near the monastery of [[Gotthard of Hildesheim|Saint Gotthar]]d and beat the Austrians back. Although initially plagued by disunity, Montecuccoli was finally able to convince Coligny and Leopold Wilhelm of Baden-Baden (commander of the Imperial detachment) to mass their forces and attack the Ottoman troops, who were reorganizing in a nearby forest. The attack surprised the Turks, who fled in confusion back to the river, a large number drowning. The confusion caused by the fleeing troops prevented Ahmed K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc (Vizier 1661-1676) from sending the rest of his army across the river and he instead retired from the field.\n\n[[File:A szentgotth\u00e1rdi csata (n\u00e9met k\u00e9p).jpg|thumb|250px|The Battle in an engraving of the era.]]\n\nOttoman casualties were heavy, significantly falling mostly on the elite corps of the army. K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc was left with an army of ill-trained irregulars and auxiliaries while Montecuccoli's casualties were light and mostly in the Imperial contingent.\n\n[[Image:Schl\u00f6sslbergi k\u0151kereszt.jpg|thumb|right|Stonecross of Sch\u00f6sslberg, over Mogersdorf; monument of the Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664).]]\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2016}}\nAlthough many in Europe, especially the [[Croats]] and [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] nobility, expected the Austrian Habsburgs to finally liberate Hungary once and for all, Leopold abandoned the campaign. Many have criticized him for this decision (both in the past and the present). Although Montecuccoli's army was largely intact, there was no interest among the allies to liberate Hungary. Any invasion of Hungary would undoubtedly have to be done without the help of the French and German troops. Leopold noticed that the French officers had begun to fraternize with the Magyar nobles and encouraged them to rebel against Austrian rule.\n\nIn addition, Leopold had always been a member of the \"Spanish faction\" in Vienna. With the last [[Habsburg Spain|Spanish Habsburg]], [[Charles II of Spain|Carlos II]], about to die at any given moment, Leopold wanted to ensure that his hands were free for the inevitable struggle against [[Louis XIV of France]]. Although the liberation of Hungary was a strategic interest of the Habsburgs, it would have to wait until later. Throughout his reign, Leopold had always been more interested in the struggle against France rather than the Ottomans. Therefore, he signed the rather unfavourable [[Peace of Vasv\u00e1r]], which did not take into account the Battle of Saint Gotthard. The Battle of Saint Gotthard is still significant, however, for it stopped any Ottoman invasion of Austria, which certainly would have prolonged the war and led to a disastrous resolution. The Austrians would also use the twenty-year truce to build up their forces and begin the liberation of Hungary in 1683.\n\n==In literature==\nThe battle of Mogersdorf/Szentgotth\u00e1rd provided [[Rainer Maria Rilke]] with the inspiration for his poetic short story, \"[[:de:Die Weise von Liebe und Tod des Cornets Christoph Rilke|Lay of the Love and Death of Cornet Christopher Rilke]]\", which was very popular among German and Austrian soldiers during the first half of the 20th century.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|War}}\n* [[Battle of Saint Gotthard (1705)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons and category|Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664)|Battle of Saint Gotthard (1664)}}\n* {{Cite ADB|35|264|267|Sporck, Johann Graf von|Felix Stieve|ADB:Sporck, Johann Graf von|ref=CITEREF1893Stieve}}\n* Jeremy Black & Rhoads Murphey, ''Ottoman Warfare, 1500-1700'', Routledge, 1999.\n* Peter H. Wilson, ''German Armies: War and German Politics, 1648-1806'', Routledge, 1998.\n*[[John P. Spielman]], ''Leopold I of Austria'' (1977) {{ISBN|0-8135-0836-3}}\n*[[Charles W. Ingrao]], ''The Habsburg Monarchy 1618-1815'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-521-78505-7}}\n\n{{Coord|46|56|30|N|16|13|00|E|dim:250_scale:2500_region:AT-1_type:event_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n{{Ottoman battles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Gotthard (1664), Battle Of}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1664]]\n[[Category:1664 in the Habsburg Monarchy]]\n[[Category:Vas County]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Hungary]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Austria|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Ottoman\u2013Hungarian Wars|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Ottoman Empire|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Moldavia|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Slovenes|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Habsburg Croatia|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Austro-Turkish War (1663\u201364)|Saint Gotthard 1664]]\n[[Category:1664 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1664 in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Wallachia]]\n", "name_user": "Nezih.oktar", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Saint_Gotthard_(1664)"}
{"title_page": "European route E20", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox road\n| country     = EUR\n| type        = E\n| route       = 20\n| map         = \n| direction_a = West\n| terminus_a  = [[Shannon Airport]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| junction    =\n| direction_b = East\n| terminus_b  = [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]\n| countries   = {{flag|Ireland}}<br>{{flag|United Kingdom}}<br>{{flag|Denmark}}<br>{{flag|Sweden}}<br>{{flag|Estonia}}<br>{{flag|Russia}}\n}}\n'''European route E20''' is a part of the [[United Nations]] [[International E-road network]]. It runs roughly west\u2013east through [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Denmark]], [[Sweden]], [[Estonia]], and [[Russia]]. \n\nIts length is {{convert|1880|km|mi|abbr=on}} but it is not continuous; at three points, a sea crossing is required. [[Roll-on/roll-off]] ferries make the crossings from [[Dublin]] to [[Liverpool]] and from [[Stockholm]] to [[Tallinn]]. No publicly accessible ferries traverse the [[North Sea]] from [[Kingston-upon-Hull]] to [[Esbjerg]] (as of 2019), but a ferry for commercial drivers leaves [[Immingham]] for Esbjerg on most days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dfds.com/en-gb/freight-shipping/routes-and-schedules/esbjerg-immingham|title=DFDS|website=www.dfds.com|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n== Route ==\n=== Ireland ===\nThe initial section of the E20 from [[Shannon Airport]] to Dublin via [[Limerick]] is approximately 228&nbsp;km long and is only partially signed, along the M7/N7. The section from Shannon Airport to east of Limerick is mainly [[dual carriageway]], with a short section of [[motorway]] as part of the Limerick Southern Ring Road. The [[Shannon Tunnel]], opened on 16 July 2010, completed the [[Bypass (road)|bypass]] of Limerick. The section from Limerick to [[Naas]] is motorway (M7), and the final section from Naas to Dublin is dual carriageway (N7). A ferry must be used from Dublin to Liverpool.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.poferries.com/en/dublin-liverpool|title=Dublin to Liverpool Ferry {{!}} Ferries to Liverpool {{!}} P&O Ferries - UK|website=www.poferries.com|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\nE20 follows the A5080 from [[Liverpool]] to [[Huyton]], the [[M62 motorway|M62]] from [[Huyton]] to [[South Cave]], and the [[A63 road|A63]] from [[South Cave]] to [[Kingston upon Hull]]. The route length across the UK is {{convert|205|km|mi}} in total but is not signposted.\n\nThere are no ferries between Kingston upon Hull and [[Esbjerg]]. Alternative ferries were once available from [[Immingham]], which is {{convert|48|km|mi}} from Kingston upon Hull, and [[Harwich]], which is {{convert|350|km|mi}} from Kingston upon Hull. There are no longer any passenger routes operating between the UK and Scandinavia.\n\nThe closest alternative is to take the [[Eurotunnel Shuttle]] from [[Cheriton, Kent|Cheriton]] (Folkestone) to [[Calais]], or take a ferry from [[Harwich]] to [[Hook of Holland]]. Both of these routes would require a detour of around 900 miles (940 miles to Esbjerg, as this route would require you to drive along the E20 to reach Esbjerg).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Kingston+upon+Hull,+Hull/Esbjerg,+Denmark/@53.1347163,0.1042165,6z/|title=Hull to Esbjerg|website=Hull to Esbjerg|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Denmark ===\nIn Denmark, E20 is a motorway from [[Esbjerg]] to the [[\u00d8resund Bridge]]. The length of the Danish part is {{convert|315|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\nIt passes first along [[Jutland]] from Esbjerg to [[Kolding]], then crosses the [[Little Belt Bridge]] onto [[Funen]]. E20 crosses the entirety of Funen, passing around 2km from Odense. Then, at [[Nyborg]], E20 crosses the [[Great Belt Fixed Link]] onto [[Zealand]]. E20 follows the Vestmotorvejen until [[K\u00f8ge]], where it goes north to Copenhagen. In Copenhagen, E20 passes south of the city, crossing onto [[Kastrup]] where it meets the [[Copenhagen Airport]]. The \u00d8resund Bridge begins as a tunnel on Kastrup.\n\nBetween [[K\u00f8ge]] and [[Copenhagen]], the road has three E-road numbers ([[European route E47|E47]] and [[European route E55|E55]]).\n\nThe Great Belt Bridge and \u00d8resund Bridge are both tolled, charging over \u20ac30 each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dk.oresundsbron.com/page/1053|title=\u00d8resundsbron|author=|date=|website=dk.oresundsbron.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storebaelt.dk/priserprodukter/priser/biler|title=Personbil - Storeb\u00e6lt|author=|date=|website=www.storebaelt.dk|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> The road crosses the border between Denmark and Sweden on the \u00d8resund Bridge.<!-- {{hidden begin|border=1px #aaa solid|title={{center|List of exits (east to west)}}}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]15 [[Copenhagen Airport|Lufthavn \u00d8]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]16 [[Copenhagen Airport|Lufthavn]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]17 [[Copenhagen Airport|Lufthavn V]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]18 [[T\u00e5rnby]] {{Riksvei|221}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]19 [[\u00d8restad]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]20 [[Copenhagen|K\u00f8benhavn C]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]21 [[Aved\u00f8re Holme]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]22 [[Gl. K\u00f8ge Landevej]] {{Riksvei|151}}\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|47|n}} {{Europavei|55|n}} [[Helsing\u00f8r]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]25 [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]] {{DRNSs|O3}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]26 [[Ish\u00f8j Strand]] {{Riksvei|243}}\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{DRNSs|O4|n}} [[Lyngby]], [[Roskilde]], [[Copenhagen]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]27 [[Greve Strand|Greve N]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]28 [[Greve Strand|Greve C]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]29 [[Greve Strand|Greve S]] {{Riksvei|217}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] | [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Karlsunde\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]30 [[Solr\u00f8d|Solr\u00f8d N]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]31 [[Solr\u00f8d|Solr\u00f8d S]] {{DRNSs|6}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]32 [[K\u00f8ge]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|47|s}} {{Europavei|55|s}} [[R\u00f8dby]], [[Gedser]]\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]| Salby\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]33 [[Vemmedrup]]\n*|[[File:Zeichen 377.svg|20px]] Bj\u00e6verskov\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]34 [[Borup, K\u00f8ge Municipality|Borup]]\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Kongsted/B\u00f8gede\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Kv\u00e6rkeby\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]35 [[Ringsted|Ringsted \u00d8]] {{DRNSs|14}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]36 [[Ringsted|Ringsted N]] {{Riksvei|215|n}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] | [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Tuels\u00f8\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]37 [[Sor\u00f8]] {{DRNSs|57}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]38 [[Slagelse|Slagelse \u00d8]] {{Riksvei|150}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Antvorskov\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]39 [[Slagelse|Slagelse S]] {{DRNSs|22}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]40 [[Vemmelev]] {{Riksvei|150}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]41 [[Tj\u00e6reby]] {{Riksvei|277}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]42 [[Kors\u00f8r]] {{Riksvei|265|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]43 [[Halskov]] [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]44 [[Knudshoved]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]45 [[Nyborg|Nyborg \u00d8]] {{Riksvei|153|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]46 [[Nyborg|Nyborg V]] {{Riksvei|165|n}} {{DRNSs|8|s}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] R\u00f8nninge\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]47 [[Langeskov]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]48 [[Tietgenbyen]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{DRNSs|9|n}} [[Svendborg]] {{DRNSs|9|s}} [[Odense]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]50 [[Hjallese]] {{Riksvei|167|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]51 [[Odense|Odense S]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]52 [[Odense|Odense SV]] {{Riksvei|168}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]53 [[Odense|Odense V]] {{Riksvei|161}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] | [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Kildebjerg\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]54 [[Vissenbjerg]] {{Riksvei|335}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]55 [[Aarup]] {{Riksvei|329}}\n*|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] \u00c5lsbo\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]56 [[Ejby, Middelfart Municipality|Ejby]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]57 [[N\u00f8rre \u00c5by]] {{Riksvei|313}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Lilleb\u00e6lt\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]58 [[Middelfart]] [[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]59 [[Fredericia|Fredericia S]] {{DRNSs|28|n}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]60 [[Fredericia|Fredericia V]] {{Riksvei|171}}\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|45|n}} [[Horsens]], [[\u00c5rhus]], [[Aalborg]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]61 [[Taulov]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|45|s}} [[Kolding]], [[Aabenraa]], [[Flensburg]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]62 [[Kolding|Kolding \u00d8]] {{Riksvei|176|v}}{{Riksvei|170}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]63 [[Bramdrupdam]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|45|s}} [[Aabenraa]], [[Flensburg]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]64 [[Kolding|Kolding V]]\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Harte\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]65 [[Lunderskov|Lunderskov \u00d8]] {{DRNSs|32|s}}{{Riksvei|191|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]66 [[Lunderskov]] {{Riksvei|469}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]67 [[Vejen|Vejen \u00d8]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]68 [[Vejen]] {{Riksvei|403|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]69 [[Br\u00f8rup]] {{Riksvei|417}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]70 [[Holsted]] {{Riksvei|425}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Bj\u00f8vlund\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]71 [[G\u00f8rding]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]72 [[Bramming]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]73 [[Korskro]] {{DRNSs|11}}{{DRNSs|30|n}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]74 [[Skads]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]75 [[Esbjerg|Esbjerg N]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]76 [[Esbjerg|Esbjerg \u00d8]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{hidden end}}\n -->\n\n=== Sweden ===\nIn Sweden, E20 is a motorway from the [[\u00d6resund Bridge]] in [[Malm\u00f6]] to N\u00e4\u00e4s 30&nbsp;km east of [[Gothenburg]], a {{convert|320|km|mi|abbr=on}} long motorway. Furthermore, it is a motorway most of the route from Vretstorp (20&nbsp;km (12&nbsp;mi) west of [[\u00d6rebro]]) to [[Stockholm]].\n\nThe Swedish part of E20 is {{convert|770|km|mi|abbr=on}} long. Its extent is shared with [[European route E6|E6]] along a {{convert|280|km|mi|abbr=on}} long stretch, with [[European route E18|E18]] along {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} and with [[European route E4|E4]] along {{convert|35|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe part through Stockholm has very heavy traffic, including the most heavily trafficked road in Scandinavia{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}, [[Essingeleden]] (160&nbsp;000 vehicles/day). There is often congestion on this stretch. A new tunnel for route E20, \"[[Norra l\u00e4nken]]\", was built north of the city center and opened 30 November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trafikverket.se/Privat/Projekt/Stockholm/E20-norra-lanken/Om_projektet/|title=Om projektet Norra l\u00e4nken|first=|last=Trafikverket|date=|website=Trafikverket|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> The planned [[F\u00f6rbifart Stockholm]] bypass will divert traffic from Essingeleden.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nBetween [[Stockholm]] and [[Tallinn]] a car ferry departs daily, taking 15 hours. The port in Stockholm is located at [[Lilla V\u00e4rtan]], about 4&nbsp;km northeast of the central core of the city.\n\n=== Estonia ===\nIn Estonia, E20 follows the route of national [[Transport in Estonia#National roads|main road]] nr. 1 (Tallinn\u2013Narva). In Tallinn to relieve traffic a bridge has been built on the intersection of the [[European route E263|E263]] and the E20. The E20 across Estonia is partially an unsigned expressway (speed limit 110&nbsp;km/h in summer), for 80.7&nbsp;km east of Tallinn to [[Aaspere]] along with a section near Haljala (km 87 - 90.5) and a section between [[Kohtla-J\u00e4rve]] and [[J\u00f5hvi]] (km 155.9\u2013163.2). The remainder being single carriageway. The distance from Tallinn to the Russian border at the [[Narva River]] is 218&nbsp;km.\n\n=== Russia ===\nIn Russia, the route takes the Narva Highway (also listed in the Russian road numbering system as the [[A180 highway (Russia)|A180 route]], formerly known as the M11 route) running from [[Ivangorod]] to [[Saint Petersburg]] as a dual-lane highway. The distance from Ivangorod to Saint Petersburg is 142&nbsp;km.\n\nThe border control facilities at the Estonia-Russia crossing are equipped and being operated for a limited amount of traffic on both sides of the border. The border crossing requires a reservation - despite this, waiting lines still can extend for many hours and even days.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title = Electronic reservation system for border crossings at the Estonia-Russia checkpoints; updates on the waiting lines. | url = https://www.eestipiir.ee/yphis/index.action}}</ref>\n\n{{gallery\n|title =E20 route, west to east\n|File:M62 motorway, Calderdale.jpg|The M62 passes [[Scammonden Reservoir]] in [[West Yorkshire]]\n|File:E20 53.jpg|E&nbsp;20 near [[Odense]], [[Denmark]]\n|File:Copenhagen airport from air.jpg|E20 next to the [[Copenhagen Airport]]\n|File:\u00d6resundsbron i solnedg\u00e5ng 2.jpg|[[Oresund Bridge]], between [[Denmark]] and [[Sweden]]\n|File:\u00d6resundsbrons vajrar 2.jpg|On Oresund Bridge\n|File:Landskrona, 2006-09-11.jpg|East coast of Oresund, between [[Malm\u00f6]] and [[Helsingborg]], showing the city of [[Landskrona]].\n|File:Tallinn-Narva maantee.jpg|Near [[J\u00e4gala]], Estonia\n||Border between [[Narva]] (Estonia) (left) and [[Ivangorod]] (Russia)\n}}\n\n== Itinerary ==\n*{{flag|Ireland}}\n**{{jct|country=IRL|N|18}}: [[Shannon, County Clare|Shannon]] - [[Limerick]]\n**{{jct|country=IRL|M|7}}: [[Limerick]] - [[Borris-in-Ossory]] ({{BAB-E|201|IE}}) - [[Portlaoise]] - [[Naas]]\n**{{jct|country=IRL|N|7}}: [[Naas]] - [[Dublin]]\n**{{jct|country=IRL|M|50}}: [[Dublin]]\n*Gap ([[Irish Sea]])\n**[[File:Ferry Sign.svg|20px|link=Ferry]]: {{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Dublin]] - {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Liverpool]]\n*{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n**{{jct|country=GBR|A|5036}}: [[Bootle]]\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|57}}: '''[[Liverpool]]''' Outer Ring Road (''Whole length'')\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|62}}: [[Huyton]] - '''[[Manchester]]''' (Interchange with {{BAB-E|5}} and start of multiplex with {{BAB-E|22}} at [[File:UK-Motorway-M6.svg|x15px|link=M6 motorway]] [[Warrington]])\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|60}}: '''[[Manchester]]''' Outer Ring Road (''Clockwise'')\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|62}}: '''[[Manchester]]''' - [[File:UK road A63.PNG|40px|link=A63 road]] (Interchange with {{BAB-E|15}} at [[File:UK-Motorway-A1(M).svg|x15px|link=A1(M) motorway]] [[Pontefract]] and end of multiplex with {{BAB-E|22}} at [[File:UK-Motorway-M18.svg|x15px|link=M18 motorway]] [[Goole]])\n**{{jct|country=GBR|A|63}}: [[File:UK-Motorway-M62.svg|x15px|link=M62 motorway]] - [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]]\n**{{jct|country=GBR|A|1033}}: [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]]\n*Gap ([[North Sea]])\n**{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] - {{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Esbjerg]]\n*{{flag|Denmark}}\n**{{BAB-E|20|DK}}: [[Esbjerg]] - [[Kolding]] ({{BAB-E|45|DK}}) - [[K\u00f8ge]] (Start of Concurrency with {{BAB-E|47|DK}} {{BAB-E|55|DK}}) - [[K\u00f8benhavn]] (End of Concurrency with {{BAB-E|47|DK}} {{BAB-E|55|DK}})\n*{{flag|Sweden}}\n**{{BAB-E|20|S}}: [[Malm\u00f6]] ({{jct|country=SWE|E|22|E|65|rdt=y}}, Start of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|6|rdt=y}}) - [[Helsingborg]] ({{jct|country=SWE|E|4|rdt=y}}) - [[Gothenburg]] ({{jct|country=SWE|E|45|rdt=y}}, End of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|6|rdt=y}}) - [[\u00d6rebro]] (Start of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|18|rdt=y}}) - [[Arboga]] (End of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|18|rdt=y}}) - [[Eskilstuna]] - [[S\u00f6dert\u00e4lje]] (Start of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|4|rdt=y}}) - [[Stockholm]] (End of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|4|rdt=y}}, Towards {{jct|country=SWE|E|18|rdt=y}})\n*Gap ([[Baltic Sea]])\n**[[File:Ferry Sign.svg|20px|link=Ferry]]: {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Stockholm]] - {{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Tallinn]]\n*{{flag|Estonia}}\n**J\u00f5e, Narva maantee, Tartu maantee: [[Tallinn]] ({{BAB-E|67|EE}})\n**{{jct|country=EST|N|1}}: [[Tallinn]] ({{BAB-E|67|EE}} {{BAB-E|263|EE}} {{BAB-E|265|EE}}) - [[J\u00f5hvi]] ({{BAB-E|264|EE}}) - [[Narva]]\n*{{flag|Russia}}\n**{{jct|country=RUS|A|180}}: [[Ivangorod]] - [[Saint Petersburg]] (Towards {{BAB-E|18|RUS}} {{BAB-E|95|RUS}} {{BAB-E|105|RUS}})\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|E20}}\n{{E-road}}\n\n[[Category:International E-road network|20]]\n[[Category:European routes in the United Kingdom|20]]\n[[Category:Roads in Denmark|E020]]\n[[Category:Roads in England|2-0020]]\n[[Category:Roads in Estonia|E020]]\n[[Category:European routes in Ireland|E020]]\n[[Category:European routes in Russia|E20]]\n[[Category:Motorways in Sweden|E020]]\n[[Category:Roads in Lancashire|2-0020]]\n[[Category:Roads in Yorkshire|2-0020]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox road\n| country     = EUR\n| type        = E\n| route       = 20\n| map         = \n| direction_a = West\n| terminus_a  = [[Shannon Airport]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| junction    =\n| direction_b = East\n| terminus_b  = [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]\n| countries   = {{flag|Ireland}}<br>{{flag|United Kingdom}}<br>{{flag|Denmark}}<br>{{flag|Sweden}}<br>{{flag|Estonia}}<br>{{flag|Russia}}\n}}\n'''European route E20''' is a part of the [[United Nations]] [[International E-road network]]. It runs roughly west\u2013east through [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Denmark]], [[Sweden]], [[Estonia]], and [[Russia]]. \n\nIts length is {{convert|1880|km|mi|abbr=on}} but it is not continuous; at three points, a sea crossing is required. [[Roll-on/roll-off]] ferries make the crossings from [[Dublin]] to [[Liverpool]] and from [[Stockholm]] to [[Tallinn]]. No publicly accessible ferries traverse the [[North Sea]] from [[Kingston-upon-Hull]] to [[Esbjerg]] (as of 2019), but a ferry for commercial drivers leaves [[Immingham]] for Esbjerg on most days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dfds.com/en-gb/freight-shipping/routes-and-schedules/esbjerg-immingham|title=DFDS|website=www.dfds.com|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n== Route ==\n=== Ireland ===\nThe initial section of the E20 from [[Shannon Airport]] to Dublin via [[Limerick]] is approximately 228&nbsp;km long and is only partially signed, along the M7/N7. The section from Shannon Airport to east of Limerick is mainly [[dual carriageway]], with a short section of [[motorway]] as part of the Limerick Southern Ring Road. The [[Shannon Tunnel]], opened on 16 July 2010, completed the [[Bypass (road)|bypass]] of Limerick. The section from Limerick to [[Naas]] is motorway (M7), and the final section from Naas to Dublin is dual carriageway (N7). A ferry must be used from Dublin to Liverpool.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.poferries.com/en/dublin-liverpool|title=Dublin to Liverpool Ferry {{!}} Ferries to Liverpool {{!}} P&O Ferries - UK|website=www.poferries.com|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\nE20 follows the A5080 from [[Liverpool]] to [[Huyton]], the [[M62 motorway|M62]] from [[Huyton]] to [[South Cave]], and the [[A63 road|A63]] from [[South Cave]] to [[Kingston upon Hull]]. The route length across the UK is {{convert|205|km|mi}} in total but is not signposted.\n\nThere are no ferries between Kingston upon Hull and [[Esbjerg]]. Alternative ferries were once available from [[Immingham]], which is {{convert|48|km|mi}} from Kingston upon Hull, and [[Harwich]], which is {{convert|350|km|mi}} from Kingston upon Hull. There are no longer any passenger routes operating between the UK and Scandinavia.\n\nThe closest alternative is to take the [[Eurotunnel Shuttle]] from [[Cheriton, Kent|Cheriton]] (Folkestone) to [[Calais]], or take a ferry from [[Harwich]] to [[Hook of Holland]]. Both of these routes would require a detour of around 900 miles (940 miles to Esbjerg, as this route would require you to drive along the E20 to reach Esbjerg).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Kingston+upon+Hull,+Hull/Esbjerg,+Denmark/@53.1347163,0.1042165,6z/|title=Hull to Esbjerg|website=Hull to Esbjerg|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Denmark ===\nIn Denmark, E20 is a motorway from [[Esbjerg]] to the [[\u00d8resund Bridge]]. The length of the Danish part is {{convert|315|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\nIt passes first along [[Jutland]] from Esbjerg to [[Kolding]], then crosses the [[Little Belt Bridge]] onto [[Funen]]. E20 crosses the entirety of Funen, passing around 2km from Odense. Then, at [[Nyborg]], E20 crosses the [[Great Belt Fixed Link]] onto [[Zealand]]. E20 follows the Vestmotorvejen until [[K\u00f8ge]], where it goes north to Copenhagen. In Copenhagen, E20 passes south of the city, crossing onto [[Kastrup]] where it meets the [[Copenhagen Airport]]. The \u00d8resund Bridge begins as a tunnel on Kastrup.\n\nBetween [[K\u00f8ge]] and [[Copenhagen]], the road has three E-road numbers ([[European route E47|E47]] and [[European route E55|E55]]).\n\nThe Great Belt Bridge and \u00d8resund Bridge are both tolled, charging over \u20ac30 each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dk.oresundsbron.com/page/1053|title=\u00d8resundsbron|author=|date=|website=dk.oresundsbron.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storebaelt.dk/priserprodukter/priser/biler|title=Personbil - Storeb\u00e6lt|author=|date=|website=www.storebaelt.dk|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> The road crosses the border between Denmark and Sweden on the \u00d8resund Bridge.<!-- {{hidden begin|border=1px #aaa solid|title={{center|List of exits (east to west)}}}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]15 [[Copenhagen Airport|Lufthavn \u00d8]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]16 [[Copenhagen Airport|Lufthavn]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]17 [[Copenhagen Airport|Lufthavn V]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]18 [[T\u00e5rnby]] {{Riksvei|221}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]19 [[\u00d8restad]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]20 [[Copenhagen|K\u00f8benhavn C]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]21 [[Aved\u00f8re Holme]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]22 [[Gl. K\u00f8ge Landevej]] {{Riksvei|151}}\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|47|n}} {{Europavei|55|n}} [[Helsing\u00f8r]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]25 [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]] {{DRNSs|O3}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]26 [[Ish\u00f8j Strand]] {{Riksvei|243}}\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{DRNSs|O4|n}} [[Lyngby]], [[Roskilde]], [[Copenhagen]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]27 [[Greve Strand|Greve N]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]28 [[Greve Strand|Greve C]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]29 [[Greve Strand|Greve S]] {{Riksvei|217}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] | [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Karlsunde\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]30 [[Solr\u00f8d|Solr\u00f8d N]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]31 [[Solr\u00f8d|Solr\u00f8d S]] {{DRNSs|6}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]32 [[K\u00f8ge]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|47|s}} {{Europavei|55|s}} [[R\u00f8dby]], [[Gedser]]\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]| Salby\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]33 [[Vemmedrup]]\n*|[[File:Zeichen 377.svg|20px]] Bj\u00e6verskov\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]34 [[Borup, K\u00f8ge Municipality|Borup]]\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Kongsted/B\u00f8gede\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Kv\u00e6rkeby\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]35 [[Ringsted|Ringsted \u00d8]] {{DRNSs|14}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]36 [[Ringsted|Ringsted N]] {{Riksvei|215|n}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] | [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Tuels\u00f8\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]37 [[Sor\u00f8]] {{DRNSs|57}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]38 [[Slagelse|Slagelse \u00d8]] {{Riksvei|150}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Antvorskov\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]39 [[Slagelse|Slagelse S]] {{DRNSs|22}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]40 [[Vemmelev]] {{Riksvei|150}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]41 [[Tj\u00e6reby]] {{Riksvei|277}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]42 [[Kors\u00f8r]] {{Riksvei|265|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]43 [[Halskov]] [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]44 [[Knudshoved]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]45 [[Nyborg|Nyborg \u00d8]] {{Riksvei|153|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]46 [[Nyborg|Nyborg V]] {{Riksvei|165|n}} {{DRNSs|8|s}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] R\u00f8nninge\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]47 [[Langeskov]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]48 [[Tietgenbyen]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{DRNSs|9|n}} [[Svendborg]] {{DRNSs|9|s}} [[Odense]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]50 [[Hjallese]] {{Riksvei|167|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]51 [[Odense|Odense S]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]52 [[Odense|Odense SV]] {{Riksvei|168}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]53 [[Odense|Odense V]] {{Riksvei|161}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] | [[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Kildebjerg\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]54 [[Vissenbjerg]] {{Riksvei|335}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]55 [[Aarup]] {{Riksvei|329}}\n*|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] \u00c5lsbo\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]56 [[Ejby, Middelfart Municipality|Ejby]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]57 [[N\u00f8rre \u00c5by]] {{Riksvei|313}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Lilleb\u00e6lt\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]58 [[Middelfart]] [[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]59 [[Fredericia|Fredericia S]] {{DRNSs|28|n}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]60 [[Fredericia|Fredericia V]] {{Riksvei|171}}\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|45|n}} [[Horsens]], [[\u00c5rhus]], [[Aalborg]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]61 [[Taulov]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|45|s}} [[Kolding]], [[Aabenraa]], [[Flensburg]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]62 [[Kolding|Kolding \u00d8]] {{Riksvei|176|v}}{{Riksvei|170}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]63 [[Bramdrupdam]]\n*[[File:AB-Kreuz-blau.svg]] {{Europavei|45|s}} [[Aabenraa]], [[Flensburg]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]64 [[Kolding|Kolding V]]\n*[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 361-50.svg|20px]][[File:Zeichen 376.svg|20px]] Harte\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]65 [[Lunderskov|Lunderskov \u00d8]] {{DRNSs|32|s}}{{Riksvei|191|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]66 [[Lunderskov]] {{Riksvei|469}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]67 [[Vejen|Vejen \u00d8]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]68 [[Vejen]] {{Riksvei|403|s}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]69 [[Br\u00f8rup]] {{Riksvei|417}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]70 [[Holsted]] {{Riksvei|425}}\n*[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]]|[[File:Zeichen 314 - Parkplatz, StVO 2013.svg|20px]] Bj\u00f8vlund\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]71 [[G\u00f8rding]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]72 [[Bramming]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]73 [[Korskro]] {{DRNSs|11}}{{DRNSs|30|n}}\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]74 [[Skads]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]75 [[Esbjerg|Esbjerg N]]\n*[[File:AB-AS.svg]]76 [[Esbjerg|Esbjerg \u00d8]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{hidden end}}\n -->\n\n=== Sweden ===\nIn Sweden, E20 is a motorway from the [[\u00d6resund Bridge]] in [[Malm\u00f6]] to N\u00e4\u00e4s 30&nbsp;km east of [[Gothenburg]], a {{convert|320|km|mi|abbr=on}} long motorway. Furthermore, it is a motorway most of the route from Vretstorp (20&nbsp;km (12&nbsp;mi) west of [[\u00d6rebro]]) to [[Stockholm]].\n\nThe Swedish part of E20 is {{convert|770|km|mi|abbr=on}} long. Its extent is shared with [[European route E6|E6]] along a {{convert|280|km|mi|abbr=on}} long stretch, with [[European route E18|E18]] along {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} and with [[European route E4|E4]] along {{convert|35|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe part through Stockholm has very heavy traffic, including the most heavily trafficed road in Scandinavia{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}, [[Essingeleden]] (160&nbsp;000 vehicles/day). There is often congestion on this stretch. A new tunnel for route E20, \"[[Norra l\u00e4nken]]\", was built north of the city center and opened 30 November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trafikverket.se/Privat/Projekt/Stockholm/E20-norra-lanken/Om_projektet/|title=Om projektet Norra l\u00e4nken|first=|last=Trafikverket|date=|website=Trafikverket|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> The planned [[F\u00f6rbifart Stockholm]] bypass will divert traffic from Essingeleden.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nBetween [[Stockholm]] and [[Tallinn]] a car ferry departs daily, taking 15 hours. The port in Stockholm is located at [[Lilla V\u00e4rtan]], about 4&nbsp;km northeast of the central core of the city.\n\n=== Estonia ===\nIn Estonia, E20 follows the route of national [[Transport in Estonia#National roads|main road]] nr. 1 (Tallinn\u2013Narva). In Tallinn to relieve traffic a bridge has been built on the intersection of the [[European route E263|E263]] and the E20. The E20 across Estonia is partially an unsigned expressway (speed limit 110&nbsp;km/h in summer), for 80.7&nbsp;km east of Tallinn to [[Aaspere]] along with a section near Haljala (km 87 - 90.5) and a section between [[Kohtla-J\u00e4rve]] and [[J\u00f5hvi]] (km 155.9\u2013163.2). The remainder being single carriageway. The distance from Tallinn to the Russian border at the [[Narva River]] is 218&nbsp;km.\n\n=== Russia ===\nIn Russia, the route takes the Narva Highway (also listed in the Russian road numbering system as the [[A180 highway (Russia)|A180 route]], formerly known as the M11 route) running from [[Ivangorod]] to [[Saint Petersburg]] as a dual-lane highway. The distance from Ivangorod to Saint Petersburg is 142&nbsp;km.\n\nThe border control facilities at the Estonia-Russia crossing are equipped and being operated for a limited amount of traffic on both sides of the border. The border crossing requires a reservation - despite this, waiting lines still can extend for many hours and even days.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title = Electronic reservation system for border crossings at the Estonia-Russia checkpoints; updates on the waiting lines. | url = https://www.eestipiir.ee/yphis/index.action}}</ref>\n\n{{gallery\n|title =E20 route, west to east\n|File:M62 motorway, Calderdale.jpg|The M62 passes [[Scammonden Reservoir]] in [[West Yorkshire]]\n|File:E20 53.jpg|E&nbsp;20 near [[Odense]], [[Denmark]]\n|File:Copenhagen airport from air.jpg|E20 next to the [[Copenhagen Airport]]\n|File:\u00d6resundsbron i solnedg\u00e5ng 2.jpg|[[Oresund Bridge]], between [[Denmark]] and [[Sweden]]\n|File:\u00d6resundsbrons vajrar 2.jpg|On Oresund Bridge\n|File:Landskrona, 2006-09-11.jpg|East coast of Oresund, between [[Malm\u00f6]] and [[Helsingborg]], showing the city of [[Landskrona]].\n|File:Tallinn-Narva maantee.jpg|Near [[J\u00e4gala]], Estonia\n||Border between [[Narva]] (Estonia) (left) and [[Ivangorod]] (Russia)\n}}\n\n== Itinerary ==\n*{{flag|Ireland}}\n**{{jct|country=IRL|N|18}}: [[Shannon, County Clare|Shannon]] - [[Limerick]]\n**{{jct|country=IRL|M|7}}: [[Limerick]] - [[Borris-in-Ossory]] ({{BAB-E|201|IE}}) - [[Portlaoise]] - [[Naas]]\n**{{jct|country=IRL|N|7}}: [[Naas]] - [[Dublin]]\n**{{jct|country=IRL|M|50}}: [[Dublin]]\n*Gap ([[Irish Sea]])\n**[[File:Ferry Sign.svg|20px|link=Ferry]]: {{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Dublin]] - {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Liverpool]]\n*{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n**{{jct|country=GBR|A|5036}}: [[Bootle]]\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|57}}: '''[[Liverpool]]''' Outer Ring Road (''Whole length'')\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|62}}: [[Huyton]] - '''[[Manchester]]''' (Interchange with {{BAB-E|5}} and start of multiplex with {{BAB-E|22}} at [[File:UK-Motorway-M6.svg|x15px|link=M6 motorway]] [[Warrington]])\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|60}}: '''[[Manchester]]''' Outer Ring Road (''Clockwise'')\n**{{jct|country=GBR|M|62}}: '''[[Manchester]]''' - [[File:UK road A63.PNG|40px|link=A63 road]] (Interchange with {{BAB-E|15}} at [[File:UK-Motorway-A1(M).svg|x15px|link=A1(M) motorway]] [[Pontefract]] and end of multiplex with {{BAB-E|22}} at [[File:UK-Motorway-M18.svg|x15px|link=M18 motorway]] [[Goole]])\n**{{jct|country=GBR|A|63}}: [[File:UK-Motorway-M62.svg|x15px|link=M62 motorway]] - [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]]\n**{{jct|country=GBR|A|1033}}: [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]]\n*Gap ([[North Sea]])\n**{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] - {{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Esbjerg]]\n*{{flag|Denmark}}\n**{{BAB-E|20|DK}}: [[Esbjerg]] - [[Kolding]] ({{BAB-E|45|DK}}) - [[K\u00f8ge]] (Start of Concurrency with {{BAB-E|47|DK}} {{BAB-E|55|DK}}) - [[K\u00f8benhavn]] (End of Concurrency with {{BAB-E|47|DK}} {{BAB-E|55|DK}})\n*{{flag|Sweden}}\n**{{BAB-E|20|S}}: [[Malm\u00f6]] ({{jct|country=SWE|E|22|E|65|rdt=y}}, Start of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|6|rdt=y}}) - [[Helsingborg]] ({{jct|country=SWE|E|4|rdt=y}}) - [[Gothenburg]] ({{jct|country=SWE|E|45|rdt=y}}, End of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|6|rdt=y}}) - [[\u00d6rebro]] (Start of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|18|rdt=y}}) - [[Arboga]] (End of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|18|rdt=y}}) - [[Eskilstuna]] - [[S\u00f6dert\u00e4lje]] (Start of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|4|rdt=y}}) - [[Stockholm]] (End of Concurrency with {{jct|country=SWE|E|4|rdt=y}}, Towards {{jct|country=SWE|E|18|rdt=y}})\n*Gap ([[Baltic Sea]])\n**[[File:Ferry Sign.svg|20px|link=Ferry]]: {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Stockholm]] - {{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Tallinn]]\n*{{flag|Estonia}}\n**J\u00f5e, Narva maantee, Tartu maantee: [[Tallinn]] ({{BAB-E|67|EE}})\n**{{jct|country=EST|N|1}}: [[Tallinn]] ({{BAB-E|67|EE}} {{BAB-E|263|EE}} {{BAB-E|265|EE}}) - [[J\u00f5hvi]] ({{BAB-E|264|EE}}) - [[Narva]]\n*{{flag|Russia}}\n**{{jct|country=RUS|A|180}}: [[Ivangorod]] - [[Saint Petersburg]] (Towards {{BAB-E|18|RUS}} {{BAB-E|95|RUS}} {{BAB-E|105|RUS}})\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|E20}}\n{{E-road}}\n\n[[Category:International E-road network|20]]\n[[Category:European routes in the United Kingdom|20]]\n[[Category:Roads in Denmark|E020]]\n[[Category:Roads in England|2-0020]]\n[[Category:Roads in Estonia|E020]]\n[[Category:European routes in Ireland|E020]]\n[[Category:European routes in Russia|E20]]\n[[Category:Motorways in Sweden|E020]]\n[[Category:Roads in Lancashire|2-0020]]\n[[Category:Roads in Yorkshire|2-0020]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSweden:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: trafficed \u2192 trafficked", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_route_E20"}
{"title_page": "Linger (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1993 single by The Cranberries}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Linger\n| cover      = CranberriesLinger.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Artwork for 1994 UK and European rereleases\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Cranberries]]\n| album      = [[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]\n| B-side     = \"Liar\", \"Reason\", \"Them\"\n| released   = 23 February 1993<br>17 February 1994 <small>(re-release)</small>\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|7\"|12\"}}\n| recorded   = 1993\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[soft rock]]}}\n| length     = 4:34 <BR> 4:11 <small>(Edit)</small>\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Dolores O'Riordan]]|[[Noel Hogan]]}}\n| producer   = [[Stephen Street]]\n| prev_title = [[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n| misc       = \n{{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Linger by The Cranberries.ogg\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|G6Kspj3OO0s|\"Linger\"}}\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = LingerUS.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Artwork for US vinyl and CD releases\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Linger'''\" is a song composed by [[Ireland|Irish]] musicians [[Dolores O'Riordan]] and [[Noel Hogan]] of the [[rock and roll|rock]] band [[The Cranberries]], released in 1993. The song, which has an acoustic arrangement featuring a string section, became the band's first major hit, peaking at #3 in the [[Republic of Ireland]], #8 in the [[United States]],<ref>[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the cranberries|chart=all}} Billboard.com].</ref> and #14 in the [[United Kingdom]]. \nThe song remained in the Billboard Hot 100 for 24 weeks.\nThe song was voted by Triple J listeners as #3 on the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 1993]] chart. In 2017, an acoustic, stripped-down version of the song was released as the lead single for the album ''[[Something Else (The Cranberries album)|Something Else]]''.<ref name=\"pitchfork3-14-2017\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/72242-listen-to-the-cranberries-new-acoustic-version-of-linger/|title=The Cranberries Announce New Acoustic Album Something Else, Share \u201cLinger\u201d: Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOriginally, the lyrics to \"Linger\" were written by Cranberries' first singer Niall Quinn. After O'Riordan was auditioned as the lead singer for the band, she wrote her own set of lyrics, turning it into a song of regret based on a 17 year-old soldier she once fell in love with.<ref>[http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=4032 \"Linger\" by The Cranberries] - ''[http://www.songfacts.com SongFacts]'' (accessed 25 August 2016)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-cranberries-the-hidden-power-of-dreams-62069/|title=The Cranberries: The Hidden Power of Dreams|last=Mundy|first=Chris|last2=Mundy|first2=Chris|date=1994-04-21|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Drummer Fergal Lawler recalled the process in an interview, saying:\n\n{{quote|It was a Sunday afternoon. She arrived with a keyboard under her arm, just set it up and played a few songs. We couldn't really hear her because she was singing through a guitar amp or something. I gave her a lift up to the bus stop and I was saying, 'Will we see you next week?' We gave her a tape of the music for 'Linger', which she took with her. The following week she came back, and she had lyrics written out and melodies and she sang along to what we were playing, and it was like, 'Oh, my God. She\u2019s great'.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |title=The Making of the Cranberries\u2019 Haunted Farewell |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-cranberries-final-album-interview-790271/ |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the [[documentary film|documentary]] ''[[Stars: The Best of 1992\u20132002#.2799 Love Life .26 Rock .27n.27 Roll|'99 Love Life & Rock 'n' Roll]]'', O'Riordan says that the song is about her first serious kiss.\n\n\"Linger\" has since become one of the band's most famous songs. In a 2012 interview, O'Riordan commented, \"I remember when [[MTV]] first put 'Linger' in heavy rotation, every time I walked into a diner or a hotel lobby, it was like, 'Jesus, man, here I am again'. It was trippy, like [[Jacob's Ladder]]. I didn't even have to take drugs\".<ref name=\"nat post\">{{cite web |last1=Kaplan |first1=Ben |title=The Cranberries: Everybody else is reuniting, so why can\u2019t they? |url=http://cranberriesworld.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2012.02.28-National-Post.pdf |publisher=National Post |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview for ''[[New Musical Express]]'', guitarist [[Noel Hogan]] said of the song:\n\n{{quote|It's only really since Dolores passed away that I've grown a proper appreciation for songs like 'Linger' and '[[Dreams_(The_Cranberries_song)|Dreams]]'. They were just songs in the set list for us; everybody else was losing their mind about them. And when I listen to them now I realise how great they are for someone so young, which I never, ever appreciated until a year ago. We must have played it a gazillion times in our lives and it just becomes a part of the set, but it\u2019s different now. We\u2019re so lucky to have left that behind, to have that legacy.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last1=Aubrey |first1=Elizabeth |title=The Cranberries on their final album: \u201cIt\u2019s like a little gift Dolores left behind\u201d |url=https://www.nme.com/music-interviews/cranberries-final-album-album-celebrates-work-dolores-gives-something-back-fans-like-little-gift-left-behind-2435965 |publisher=NME |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\n== Critical reception ==\nJason Elias of [[AllMusic]] described \"Linger\" as \"a song of regret, epic in scope and sweeping\", praising the instrumentation and O'Riordan vocals: \"While this isn't lyrically novel, the full-on emotionality of lead singer Dolores O'Riordan makes this stand out. Singing in a strong Irish brogue she comes off both needy and detached here. It's that emotion that powers this track\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/linger-mt0038478889|title=Linger - The Cranberries {{!}} Song Info|last=Elias|first=Jason|date=|website=[[AllMusic]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\nThe song ranked at number 86 on [[Vh1]]'s 100 Greatest Songs of the '90s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spinditty.com/playlists/Top-100-Songs-of-the-90s|title=VH1's 100 Greatest Songs of the '90s|website=spinditty.com|date=18 November 2018|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"Linger\", shot in [[grayscale]], is a tribute to [[Jean-Luc Godard]]'s 1965 science fiction [[Film noir|noir film]] ''[[Alphaville (film)|Alphaville]]''. In one of the rooms of the hotel a silent film is being shown which features 1950s stripper [[Blaze Starr]].<ref>{{YouTube|G6Kspj3OO0s|The Cranberries - Linger}} (uploaded 16 June 2009)</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{unreferenced section|date=October 2017}}\n;North American CD Single (1993)\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"Liar\" <small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 2:22\n# \"Them\" <small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 3:43\n# \"Reason\"<small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 2:02\n:<small>\"Liar\" has previously appeared on the ''[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]'' single. \"Them\" and \"Reason\" are written by Dolores O'Riordan and Noel Hogan.</small>\n\n;UK and European 12\" Single\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"Reason\" <small