Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.2687&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.2687.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.2687|title=RPM Top 100 Hit Tracks of 1994|work=RPM|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|47\n|-\n|Canada Adult Contemporary (''RPM'')<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.7995&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.7995.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.7995|title=RPM Top 100 AC tracks of 1994|work=RPM|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|68\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>[http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1994.htm Musicoutfitters.com]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|49\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Country\n!Certification\n!Date\n!Sales certified\n|-\n|United Kingdom<ref>BPI certifications {{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/bpi-awards/|title=BPI Awards|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|Gold\n|align=\"center\"|9 March 2018\n|align=\"center\"|400,000\n|-\n|United States<ref>RIAA23434\n certifications {{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table%3DSEARCH_RESULTS |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626051113/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS |archivedate=2007-06-26 }} (Retrieved 29 September 2011)</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|Gold\n|align=\"center\"|26 January 1994\n|align=\"center\"|500,000\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Usage in media==\nThe song was used in episode 18 of the second season of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC's]] show ''[[Don't Trust the B---- in Apartment 23]]'' where one of the main characters June called it \"her breakup song\". \"Linger\" also appeared on an episode of ''[[Hindsight (TV series)|Hindsight]]''.\n\nThe song was also used in the 1994 movie ''[[Camp Nowhere]]'' and in the 2006 movie ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'' where it first played during the bar scene. In addition, Dolores O'Riordan made an appearance performing \"Linger\" in the wedding reception scene.\n\nThe song was heard on the television show ''[[NCIS (TV Series)|NCIS]]'' (S16 Ep 14 \"Once Upon a Tim\").\n\nThe song was used in the third episode of season two of Amy Schumer\u2019s ''[[Inside Amy Schumer]]'', during the \u201cCalling the Cable Company\u201d skit.\n\n==Covers==\n*Brazilian [[TV host]] [[Ang\u00e9lica (presenter)|Ang\u00e9lica]] sang a cover version titled \"Se A Gente Se Entender\" (\"If We Understand Each Other\"), which also received a music video.\n*Chicago punk band [[Screeching Weasel]] covered the song on their album ''[[Emo (album)|Emo]]''.\n*Dolores O'Riordan sang this song as a duet with [[Simon Le Bon]] at the [[Pavarotti & Friends for the Children of Bosnia|Pavarotti & Friends Concert for the Children of Bosnia]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jxSwun3XMZQ</ref>\n*[[Kelly Clarkson]] has covered the song.\n*Collegiate a cappella group the [[Beelzebubs]] covered the song on their album ''Pand\u00e6monium''.\n*The Malaysian band called [[Estranged (band)|Estranged]] made a cover of this track to be included on their second album, ''Anugerah Hidup''.\n*A section of the song is sung with the lyrics changed  in the NBC comedy ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''.\n*American [[indie rock]] band [[Real Estate (band)|Real Estate]] performed a version of the song in August 2014 for ''[[The A.V. Club]]''{{'s}} A.V. Undercover series.<ref>{{cite web|first= Josh |last= Modell |title= Real Estate covers The Cranberries |url= http://www.avclub.com/video/real-estate-covers-cranberries-208091 |work= [[The A.V. Club]] |publisher= [[The Onion|Onion, Inc.]] |date= 19 August 2014 |accessdate= 19 August 2014}}</ref>\n*Pakistani-American singer [[Nadia Ali (singer)|Nadia Ali]] released a cover of the song in 2018 under her side-project HYLLS.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.onestowatch.com/blog/exclusive-premiere-nadia-ali-steps-out-of-the |title= EXCLUSIVE PREMIERE: Nadia Ali Steps Out of the Nightclub & Into the Spotlight with New Project, HYLLS |date= 28 January 2018 |last= Damoui |first= Yasmin |work= Ones To Watch|accessdate= 18 February 2018 |archiveurl=  https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210558/http://www.onestowatch.com/blog/exclusive-premiere-nadia-ali-steps-out-of-the |url-status= live |archivedate=18 February 2018 }}</ref>\n*American [[pop punk]] band [[Punchline (band)]] have covered the song.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{The Cranberries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linger (Song)}}\n[[Category:The Cranberries songs]]\n[[Category:1993 singles]]\n[[Category:2017 singles]]\n[[Category:Rock ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dolores O'Riordan]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Noel Hogan]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Stephen Street]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white music videos]]\n[[Category:1992 songs]]\n[[Category:Island Records singles]]\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1993 single by The Cranberries}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Linger\n| cover      = CranberriesLinger.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Artwork for 1994 UK and European rereleases\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Cranberries]]\n| album      = [[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]\n| B-side     = \"Liar\", \"Reason\", \"Them\"\n| released   = 23 February 1993<br>17 February 1994 <small>(re-release)</small>\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|7\"|12\"}}\n| recorded   = 1993\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[soft rock]]}}\n| length     = 4:34 <BR> 4:11 <small>(Edit)</small>\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Dolores O'Riordan]]|[[Noel Hogan]]}}\n| producer   = [[Stephen Street]]\n| prev_title = [[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n| misc       = \n{{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Linger by The Cranberries.ogg\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|G6Kspj3OO0s|\"Linger\"}}\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = LingerUS.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Artwork for US vinyl and CD releases\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Linger'''\" is a song composed by [[Ireland|Irish]] musicians [[Dolores O'Riordan]] and [[Noel Hogan]] of the [[rock and roll|rock]] band [[The Cranberries]], released in 1993. The song, which has an acoustic arrangement featuring a string section, became the band's first major hit, peaking at #3 in the [[Republic of Ireland]], #8 in the [[United States]],<ref>[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the cranberries|chart=all}} Billboard.com].</ref> and #14 in the [[United Kingdom]]. \nThe song remained in the Billboard Hot 100 for 24 weeks.\nThe song was voted by Triple J listeners as #3 on the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 1993]] chart. In 2017, an acoustic, stripped-down version of the song was released as the lead single for the album ''[[Something Else (The Cranberries album)|Something Else]]''.<ref name=\"pitchfork3-14-2017\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/72242-listen-to-the-cranberries-new-acoustic-version-of-linger/|title=The Cranberries Announce New Acoustic Album Something Else, Share \u201cLinger\u201d: Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOriginally, the lyrics to \"Linger\" were written by Cranberries' first singer Niall Quinn. After O'Riordan was auditioned as the lead singer for the band, she wrote her own set of lyrics, turning it into a song of regret based on a 17 year-old soldier she once fell in love with.<ref>[http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=4032 \"Linger\" by The Cranberries] - ''[http://www.songfacts.com SongFacts]'' (accessed 25 August 2016)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-cranberries-the-hidden-power-of-dreams-62069/|title=The Cranberries: The Hidden Power of Dreams|last=Mundy|first=Chris|last2=Mundy|first2=Chris|date=1994-04-21|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Drummer Fergal Lawler recalled the process in an interview, saying:\n\n{{quote|It was a Sunday afternoon. She arrived with a keyboard under her arm, just set it up and played a few songs. We couldn't really hear her because she was singing through a guitar amp or something. I gave her a lift up to the bus stop and I was saying, 'Will we see you next week?' We gave her a tape of the music for 'Linger', which she took with her. The following week she came back, and she had lyrics written out and melodies and she sang along to what we were playing, and it was like, 'Oh, my God. She\u2019s great'.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=David |title=The Making of the Cranberries\u2019 Haunted Farewell |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-cranberries-final-album-interview-790271/ |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the [[documentary film|documentary]] ''[[Stars: The Best of 1992\u20132002#.2799 Love Life .26 Rock .27n.27 Roll|'99 Love Life & Rock 'n' Roll]]'', O'Riordan says that the song is about her first serious kiss.\n\n\"Linger\" has since become one of the band's most famous songs. In a 2012 interview, O'Riordan commented, \"I remember when [[MTV]] first put 'Linger' in heavy rotation, every time I walked into a diner or a hotel lobby, it was like, 'Jesus, man, here I am again'. It was trippy, like [[Jacob's Ladder]]. I didn't even have to take drugs\".<ref name=\"nat post\">{{cite web |last1=Kaplan |first1=Ben |title=The Cranberries: Everybody else is reuniting, so why can\u2019t they? |url=http://cranberriesworld.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2012.02.28-National-Post.pdf |publisher=National Post |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview for ''[[New Musical Express]]'', guitarist [[Noel Hogan]] said of the song:\n\n{{quote|It's only really since Dolores passed away that I've grown a proper appreciation for songs like 'Linger' and '[[Dreams_(The_Cranberries_song)|Dreams]]'. They were just songs in the set list for us; everybody else was losing their mind about them. And when I listen to them now I realise how great they are for someone so young, which I never, ever appreciated until a year ago. We must have played it a gazillion times in our lives and it just becomes a part of the set, but it\u2019s different now. We\u2019re so lucky to have left that behind, to have that legacy.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last1=Aubrey |first1=Elizabeth |title=The Cranberries on their final album: \u201cIt\u2019s like a little gift Dolores left behind\u201d |url=https://www.nme.com/music-interviews/cranberries-final-album-album-celebrates-work-dolores-gives-something-back-fans-like-little-gift-left-behind-2435965 |publisher=NME |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\n== Critical reception ==\nJason Elias of [[AllMusic]] described \"Linger\" as \"a song of regret, epic in scope and sweeping\", praising the instrumentation and O'Riordan vocals: \"While this isn't lyrically novel, the full-on emotionality of lead singer Dolores O'Riordan makes this stand out. Singing in a strong Irish brogue she comes off both needy and detached here. It's that emotion that powers this track\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/linger-mt0038478889|title=Linger - The Cranberries {{!}} Song Info|last=Elias|first=Jason|date=|website=[[AllMusic]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\nThe song ranked at number 86 on [[Vh1]]'s 100 Greatest Songs of the '90s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spinditty.com/playlists/Top-100-Songs-of-the-90s|title=VH1's 100 Greatest Songs of the '90s|website=[[Spinditty (website)|Spinditty]]|date=18 November 2018|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"Linger\", shot in [[grayscale]], is a tribute to [[Jean-Luc Godard]]'s 1965 science fiction [[Film noir|noir film]] ''[[Alphaville (film)|Alphaville]]''. In one of the rooms of the hotel a silent film is being shown which features 1950s stripper [[Blaze Starr]].<ref>{{YouTube|G6Kspj3OO0s|The Cranberries - Linger}} (uploaded 16 June 2009)</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{unreferenced section|date=October 2017}}\n;North American CD Single (1993)\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"Liar\" <small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 2:22\n# \"Them\" <small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 3:43\n# \"Reason\"<small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 2:02\n:<small>\"Liar\" has previously appeared on the ''[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]'' single. \"Them\" and \"Reason\" are written by Dolores O'Riordan and Noel Hogan.</small>\n\n;UK and European 12\" Single\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"Reason\" <small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 2:02\n# \"How\" <small>(Radical Mix)</small> \u2013 2:58\n\n;US CD Single/Promo\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Edit)</small> \u2013 4:11\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n\n;US 7\" Single/Promo\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:32\n;Cassette Singles\n:<small>'''US Cassingle'''</small> \n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"How\" \u2013 2:56\n:<small>'''UK Cassingle'''</small> \n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"Reason\" <small>(Previously Unreleased)</small> \u2013 2:02\n\n;UK and European CD Single (1994)\n# \"Linger\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2013 4:34\n# \"Pretty\" \u2013 2:16\n# \"Waltzing Back\" <small>(Live at The Record Plant, Hollywood)</small> \u2013 4:01\n# \"Pretty\" <small>(Live at The Record Plant, Hollywood)</small> \u2013 2:11\n\